<Control name="CatalogIndexPage">

<prototype>
<SitePage title="QuickUI Catalog" area="Catalog">

	<navigationLinks>
		<CatalogNavigationLinks/>
	</navigationLinks>

	<p>
	The QuickUI Catalog shows live examples of QuickUI controls, many
	designed to be ready-to-use base classes for new controls.
	(Note: Many controls depend on other controls, either for base classes,
	or as contained elements within a given control. Because QuickUI does
	not yet offer a dependency-management, for now it's necessary to download
	all dependencies by hand. Automating this process is on the QuickUI
	roadmap.
	</p>

    <p>
    The source code for these controls is available in the 
    <Link href="https://github.com/JanMiksovsky/quickui-catalog">
        quickui-catalog repository
    </Link> on GitHub.
    </p>
	
	<div id="table">
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>AutoSizeTextBox</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A text area that expands to contain its text.</div>
        </div>
	    <div>
	        <div><CatalogLink>BrowserSpecific</CatalogLink></div>
	        <div>Conditionally shows contents for specific browsers.</div>
	    </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>ButtonBase</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Base class for buttons which handles tracking of button states.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>ComboBox</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Base class for a combo box: a text input area with a dropdown set of choices.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>DeviceSpecific</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                Conditionally loads different content, control class, or styles
                depending on the type of device.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Dialog</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Base class for modal dialogs.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Fader</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Fades out content on the right or bottom instead of clipping it.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>CatalogPage</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>The template for all pages in this gallery.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Gradient</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A browser-agnostic gradient representation.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>HasPopup</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A control that has an associated popup that will appear above or below the control.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>HintTextBox</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A text box that displays a hint (instructions) when the text box is empty.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>HorizontalPanels</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                A layout control that arranges left and/or right side panels.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>List</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                An abstract control that represents each element of a JavaScript
                array as a QuickUI control.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>LoremIpsum</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Generates placeholder text.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>MultiLineText</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>Displays text that may have line breaks and/or HTML entities.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Page</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                Base class for creating top-level pages.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Popup</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                Base class for popups, menus, dialogs â€” things that temporarily appear over other things.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>SampleSpriteButton</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>An example of creating a sprite button through subclassing.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>SearchBox</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A typical web search box.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Sprite</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A basic CSS sprite.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>SpriteButton</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A button that uses a sprite for its background.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Switch</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                Something like a JavaScript switch statement, this shows exactly
                one child at any given time (e.g., to reflect an UI mode).
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>Tag</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>A simple HTML macro that includes both content and styling.</div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>TextBoxWithButton</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                A control with a text box and an associated button, where clicking
                the button does something with the text box's content.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>TextCondenser</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                Switches to a condensed font when necessary to squeeze in more text.
            </div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <div><CatalogLink>VerticalPanels</CatalogLink></div>
            <div>
                A layout control that arranges top and/or bottom panels.
            </div>
        </div>
	</div>

</SitePage>
</prototype>

<style>
#table {
    display: table;
}
#table > * {
    display: table-row;
}
#table > * > * {
    display: table-cell;
    padding-bottom: .5em;
}
#table > * > *:not(:last-child) {
    padding-right: 1em;
}
</style>

</Control>